 United Kingdom":"Preston, Northumberland, England, United Kingdom","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Harbottle","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["English (Northumberland and Durham): habitational name from Harbottle (Northumberland). The placename appears to derive from Old English <i>hȳra</i> ‘hireling’ or <i>hȳr</i> ‘hire, wages’ + <i>bōtl</i> ‘dwelling, house’."],"variants":[]},{"name":"Robert","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["One of the many French names of Germanic origin that were introduced into Britain by the Normans; it has since remained in continuous use. It is derived from the nearly synonymous elements <i>hrōd</i> ‘fame’ + <i>berht</i> ‘bright, famous’, and had a native Old English predecessor of similar form (<i>Hreodbeorht</i>), which was supplanted by the Norman name. Two dukes of Normandy in the 11th century bore the name: the father of  William the Conqueror  (sometimes identified with the legendary Robert the Devil), and his eldest son. It was borne also by three kings of Scotland, notably  Robert the Bruce  (  1274–1329 ), who freed Scotland from English domination. The altered short form <i>Bob</i> is very common, but <i>Hob</i> and <i>Dob</i>, which were common in the Middle Ages and gave rise to surnames, are extinct.  See also  Rupert ."],"variants":[]}],"lifeSummary":"Robert Harbottle was born in 1370, in Preston, Northumberland, England, United Kingdom. He married Isabel Monbourcher in 1401, in Preston, Yorkshire East Riding, England, United Kingdom. They were the parents of at least 3 sons. He died on 6 May 1419, in his hometown, at the age of 49."},"et":{"1370–6 May 1419":"1370–6. mai 1419","1369–1426":"1369–1426","1401–1443":"1401–1443","1403–1465":"1403–1465","1370–1419":"1370–1419","1426":"1426","1403":"1403","1369":"1369","1401":"1401","1465":"1465","1443":"1443","6 May 1419":"6. mai